{"cursor":"20268","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Anatomy | Name = Epidermis| Latin = Epidermis| GraySubject = |\nGrayPage = | Image = Epidermis-delimited.JPG | Caption = Histologic image of\nepidermis, delimited by white bar. | Image2 = Epidermal layers.png | Caption2 =\nHistologic image detailing epidermal layers. Stratum corneum appears more\ncompact in this image than above because of different sample preparation. |\nPrecursor = | System = | Artery = | Vein = | Nerve = | Lymph = | MeshName = |\nMeshNumber = | Code = TH H13.12.00.1.01001 TA A16.0.00.009 | }} The\n'epidermis' is composed of the outermost layers of cells in the skin, James, William; Berger, Timothy; Elston, Dirk (2005) Andrews'\nDiseases of the Skin: Clinical Dermatology (10th ed.). Saunders. Page 2-3. ISBN\n0-7216-2921-0. \"epi\" in Greek meaning \"over\" or \"upon\", which together\nwith the dermis forms the cutis.\n\nThe epidermis is a stratified squamous epithelium, {{cite book\n | last1=McGrath |first1=J.A. |last2=Eady|first2=R.A. |last3=Pope|first3=F.M.\n | title=Rook's Textbook of Dermatology year=2004 | edition=7th\n | publisher=Blackwell Publishing | isbn=978-0-632-06429-8 pages=3.1â3.6\n}} composed of proliferating basal and differentiated suprabasal\nkeratinocytes which acts as the body's major barrier against an inhospitable\nenvironment, by preventing pathogens from entering, making the skin a natural\nbarrier to infection. {{cite book\n | last1=Marks|first1=James G |last2=Miller|first2=Jeffery title=Lookingbill and\n | Marks' Principles of Dermatology | edition=4th publisher=Elsevier | year=2006\n | | pages=1â7 | isbn=1-4160-3185-5\n}} It also regulates the amount of water released from the body into\nthe atmosphere through transepidermal water loss (TEWL). {{cite journal\n | last1=Proksch |first1=E. |last2=Brandner |first2=J. |last3=Jensen|first3=J.M.\n | title=The skin: an indispensable barrier year=2008 journal=Experimental\n | Dermatology volume=17 issue=12 pages=1063â1072 doi=10.1111/j.1600-\n | 0625.2008.00786.x pmid=19043850\n}}\n\nIn humans, it is thinnest on the eyelids at and thickest on the palms and soles\nat . {{cite web\n | last=Brannon | first=Heather title=Dermatology - Epidermis\n | publisher=About.com | year=2007 url=\n | http://dermatology.about.com/cs/skinanatomy/g/epidermis.htm\n}} It is ectodermal in origin.\n","linknr":686,"url":"Epidermis_(skin)","recorded":1362554710,"links":52,"instances":["psychological","biophysical","anatomy","foot","cell_biology","biology","biology"],"pdf":["http://archderm.ama-assn.org/cgi/reprint/120/3/324.pdf","http://www.radcliffe-oxford.com/books/samplechapter/7750/01_bensouillah-241a6c80rdz.pdf"],"categories":["Skin anatomy"],"headings":["Structure","Organogenesis","Function","Culture","Disease","Additional images","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Epidermis-delimited.JPG/250px-Epidermis-delimited.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e4/Epidermal_layers.png/250px-Epidermal_layers.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/20/Skinlayers.png/220px-Skinlayers.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Normal_Epidermis_and_Dermis_with_Intradermal_Nevus_10x.JPG/150px-Normal_Epidermis_and_Dermis_with_Intradermal_Nevus_10x.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/Skin.png/146px-Skin.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/HautFingerspitzeOCT.gif/144px-HautFingerspitzeOCT.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["cell","biology"],["cutis","anatomy"],["environment","biophysical"],["sole","foot"],["sole","foot"],["sole","foot"],["cell","biology"],["cell","biology"],["tissue","biolo